{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8b9be2c1-26d5-4830-8a11-4967f5452b9d","content":"Here's how to connect the MCP Inspector to your C# stdio server:\n\n**1. Run the Inspector**\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection**\n- **Transport**: Select `STDIO`\n- **Command**: `dotnet`\n- **Arguments**: `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n  *(or point to your built DLL: `dotnet /path/to/YourServer.dll`)*\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"**\n\n**4. Debug in the UI**\n- **Tools tab** — lists discovered tools; click one to invoke it with test inputs.\n- **Resources / Prompts tabs** — test those capabilities if exposed.\n- **Notifications pane** — shows protocol-level messages (JSON-RPC traffic).\n\n**Tips**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** and logs/diagnostics to **stderr** — anything else on stdout breaks the protocol.\n- If you need environment variables, add them in the Inspector's **Environment Variables** section before connecting.\n- For faster iteration, build first (`dotnet build`) then point the command at the DLL directly to skip the build step each time.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"684dd42c-58a9-4aea-8f0c-36d9d254f503","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to explore any codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":377,"requestId":"F04A:2DF061:1260DB1:14BB8FB:69F940E9"},"id":"2193b343-6f71-4c7b-b1ca-39d1b2a2f6d8","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:59:31.866Z","parentId":"d28e9550-5cd6-4091-8c7e-5ac0def2da60"}
